ial debates, the essays in this collection explore the many difficulties created by the fact that white scholars greatly outnumber black scholars in the study and teaching of African American literature. Contributors, including some of the most prominent theorists in the field as well as younger scholars, examine who is speaking, what is being spoken and what is not, and why framing African American literature in terms of an exclusive black/white racial divide is problematic and limiting. In highlighting the "whiteness" of some African Americanists, the collection does not imply that the teaching or understanding of black literature by white scholars is definitively impossible. Indeed such work is not only possible, but imperative. Instead, the essays aim to open a much needed public conversation about the real and pressing challenges that white scholars face in this type of work, as well as the implications of how these challenges are met.   aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 23. Jun 2020) 0aAfrican AmericansxHistoriography. 0aAfrican AmericansxIntellectual life. 0aAfrican AmericansxStudy and teaching (Higher). 0aAmerican literaturexAfrican American authorsxStudy and teaching. 0aEducation, HigherxPolitical aspectsxUnited States. 0aEducation, HigherxPolitical aspectszUnited States. 0aEducation, HigherxSocial aspectsxUnited States. 0aEducation, HigherxSocial aspectszUnited States. 0aTeachers, WhitexUnited States. 0aTeachers, WhitezUnited States. 0aWhitesxIntellectual lifexUnited States. 0aWhiteszUnited StatesxIntellectual life. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / General.2bisacsh1 aLong, Lisa, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertRUP Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311068861008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertRUP Backli